issues.body:
Hey dear team,

I am experiencing memory issues in the creation and computation/optimization of large likelihood functions (that consist of a codon model, such as RELAX, and multiple alignments and trees).

The issue is detectable also when creating a likelihood function with a single alignment and tree, with a simpler, nucleotide model, such as GTR:

```
// process input
alignment_path = io.PromptUserForString("\n>Provide full path to seqData.txt");
tree_path = io.PromptUserForString("\n>Provide full path to unlabeled_tree.txt");
DataSet alignment = ReadDataFile(alignment_path);
DataSetFilter data_filter = CreateFilter (alignment, 1);
fscanf(tree_path, "String", TreeStr);

// generate a model
Freqs = {{0.25},{0.25},{0.25},{0.25}};
RateMatrix = {{*,a*t,b*t,c*t}
			  {a*t,*,d*t,e*t}
			  {b*t,d*t,*,f*t}
			  {c*t,e*t,f*t,*}};
Model model = (RateMatrix, Freqs); 
Tree tree = TreeStr;

// generate a likelihood function
LikelihoodFunction lf = (data_filter, tree);
fprintf(stdout, "lf: ", lf, "\n"); 

// compute the likelihood function
num = io.PromptUser("\n>calling  ComputeLF. Press some number to continue", 0, 1, 10, FALSE);
estimators.ComputeLF (&lf);
num = io.PromptUser("\n>calling  ComputeLF. Press some number to finish", 0, 1, 10, FALSE);

// optimize the likelihood function
num = io.PromptUser("\n>calling  Optimize. Press some number to continue", 0, 1, 10, FALSE);
Optimize (MLEs, lf);
num = io.PromptUser("\n>calling  Optimize. Press some number to finish", 0, 1, 10, FALSE);
```

In the above example, one can detect (using the command `free` between the prompts in the above code) a spike of:
approximately 25 mega when creating the likelihood function. 
approximately 30 mega when computing the log likelihood. 
approximately 100 mega when optimizing. 

When using a codon model and multiple copies of alignments and trees, the creation of the likelihood function causes a spike of around 150 mega, and is time consuming as well. The spike in the computation of the log likelihood and optimization is larger, accordingly.

Is there a way to bypass this issue? I will state that I am using multiple copies of the same codon alignment in my function (since using a reference of the same copy caused an error when I tried to delete the likelihood function, due to multiple attempts to delete the same data filter). 

Additionally, Is there a way to extract the log likelihood value from the likelihood function, rather than computing it again using estimtors.ComputeLF()? I can see it's already computed in the creation of the likelihood function when I print the instance:

```
Log Likelihood =       -4.8e+101;
Tree tree=...
```

Many thanks!
Keren

