Hi hyphyinfant,

Let me answer your questions in order.

#### Vector maximum

If you have a vector or a matrix you can call the Max or Min function on it directly. The second argument indicates whether or not you also want the **index** of the element which yields the value. 
If you set the second argument to a non-zero value, the return value will be a 2-element vector, with the [0] index storing the max/min value, and the [1] index storing the index in the original vector where this element can be found.

```
vector = {{10,4,-5,21,0}};

fprintf (stdout, "\nVector min = ", 
                 Min (vector, 0), 
                 "\nVector max = ", 
                 Max (vector, 0), 
                 "\n");

fprintf (stdout, "\nVector max with index = ", Max (vector, 1), "\n");
```

#### Reading Excel data

If you export an Excel sheet to a CSV or a tab-separated file, you can use the functions in **ReadDelimitedFiles** to read it in. For example

```
LoadFunctionLibrary ("ReadDelimitedFiles");

csv_data = ReadCSVTable ("test.csv", 1);

fprintf (stdout, "\nColumn headers:", csv_data[0],
                 "\nTable data:", csv_data[1], "\n");
```

If you pass an empty string as the first argument to **ReadCSVTable**, HyPhy will prompt you for a file; the second argument controls if you expect the CSV file to have a row of headers.

#### Generating random values from a Gaussian.

The **ProbabilityDistribution** has a function to sample from the standard normal using the Box-Muller transform. To generate normal deviates with mean mu and std.dev sigma, all you have to do is linearly transform your samples. 

```
LoadFunctionLibrary ("ProbabilityDistributions");

// populate a vector with standard normals
// the syntax below simply applies the formula 'sampleFromNormal'
// to each entry in the matrix

random_normal_values = {1000, 1} ["sampleFromNormal()"]; 

mu = 10;
sigma = 0.1;

// transform the deviates using matrix arithmetic

random_normal_values = random_normal_values * sigma + mu;

// confirm that we got what we wanted

LoadFunctionLibrary ("DescriptiveStatistics");

PrintDescriptiveStats ("Random deviates with mean " + mu + " and std.dev " + sigma,
                        GatherDescriptiveStats (random_normal_values));
```

#### Gaussian density and CDF

You can always define the standard Gaussian density as a function (it is not a part of the ProbabilityDistributions file, which I realize is not what you would expect), and its cumulative distribution function (in terms of the error function), and then simply call them to get the density values, and percentiles. For example:

```
// lfunction will give the variables inside the function a local scope         

lfunction GaussianDensity (x, mu, sigma) {
    return Exp (- (x-mu)^2 * 0.5 / sigma^2) / sigma / Sqrt (8*Arctan (1));
}

function GaussianPercentile (prob, mu, sigma) {
    // ZCDF is the standard normal cumulative distribution function
    // FindRoot is documented here http://hyphy.org/w/index.php/FindRoot
    FindRoot (z, ZCDF ((t-mu)/sigma) - prob, t, -100, 100);
    return z;

}

for (x = 0; x < 5; x+=0.5) {
    fprintf (stdout, "Normal (", x, ", mu = ", 2, ", sigma = ", 1.5, ") = ",
                      GaussianDensity (x, 2, 1.5), "\n");
}

for (x = 0.05; x < 1; x+=0.05) {
    fprintf (stdout, Format (x*100, 5, 0), " percentile of Normal (mu = ", 2, ", sigma = ", 1.5, ") = ",
                      GaussianPercentile (x, 2, 1.5), "\n");
}
```

