Hi hyphyinfant,

I'll write separate responses for each of your questions.

HyPhy includes a built-in multinomial sampler to allow you to generate a large set of replicates from a  discrete distribution.

For example, here's how you sample 100 replicates from a 10-bin distribution:

```
unique_values = 10;

CDF = {unique_values,2}; 
// first column -- which value to sample
// second column -- the corresponding probability
// HyPhy will automatically normalize them to sum to 1.

for (k = 0; k < unique_values; k+=1) {
    CDF[k][1] = 1/ (1+k);
    CDF[k][0] = k;
}


number_of_draws = 100;
binned_replicates = Random(CDF, {"PDF":"Multinomial","ARG0":number_of_draws});

fprintf (stdout, binned_replicates, "\n");
```

The result is something like this (varies from run to run, of course)

```
{
    {0,38}
    {1,13}
    {2,9}
    {3,10}
    {4,8}
    {5,9}
    {6,4}
    {7,3}
    {8,2}
    {9,4}
}
```

This trick doesn't help you to generate the samples one at a time, because you simply get counts of how often each value was sampled. You can use this trick to expand it into a vector of individual draws (this code should be made into a function if reused, of course)

```
// now convert these replicates to a serial sample

serial_samples = {1,number_of_draws};

sample_index = 0;
current_value = 0;
for (;;) {
    if (sample_index == binned_replicates[current_value][1]) {
        current_value += 1;
        if (current_value == unique_values) {
            break;
        } 
        binned_replicates[current_value][1] += binned_replicates[current_value-1][1];
    }   
    serial_samples [sample_index] = binned_replicates[current_value][0];
    sample_index += 1;

}

// Randomize ordering

serial_samples = Random (serial_samples, 0);

fprintf (stdout, serial_samples, "\n");
```

