Hi Miguel,

Use the `LFCompute` command. This is the sequence, assuming `lfID` is the name of an existing likelihood function object.

```
LFCompute (lfID,LF_START_COMPUTE);
LFCompute (lfID, current_value);
LFCompute (lfID,LF_DONE_COMPUTE);
```

The first and the last line are to set up and tear down the data structures needed to compute a LF (like large caches etc), but between the two you can change parameter values and compute the LF as many times as you want.

Sergei

Hi Stephanie, 

`MULTIPLY_BY_FREQS` is just the shortcut to avoid explicitly multiplying by &pi;<sub>c</sub> in the canonical rate matrix form.

To estimate frequencies using ML, you should define them parametrically (and normalize to 1, e.g. using a stick-breaking distribution trick). 

For example could define the vector of frequencies as follows:

```

global aux_1 = 0.5; aux_1 :< 1;
global aux_2 = 0.5; aux_2 :< 1;
global aux_3 = 0.5; aux_3 :< 1;

ML_Freqs = {{
aux_1, /*A*/
(1-aux_1)*aux_2, /*C*/
(1-aux_1)*(1-aux_2)*aux_3, /*G*/
(1-aux_1)*(1-aux_2)*(1-aux_3) /*T; note that the 4 frequencies will always be in [0,1] and sum to 1*/
}};

```

You can then pass ML_Freqs to the `Model` construct much like you would a vector of empirical frequencies.

Sergei

